{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_57","type":"agent_message","text":"The reproduced failure under the pinned GraalVM was not a missing `reachability-metadata.json` entry. `org.openjdk.jol:jol-core:0.4` was failing because the new HotSpot SA helper tests were inheriting parent JVM/native runtime arguments and, in one case, reading subprocess output in a brittle way. I fixed that in [HS_SA_SupportTest.java](/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/forge_worktrees/7602-9939c398/tests/src/org.openjdk.jol/jol-core/0.4/src/test/java/org_openjdk_jol/jol_core/HS_SA_SupportTest.java) and [HS_SA_CompressedReferencesProcessorTest.java](/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/forge_worktrees/7602-9939c398/tests/src/org.openjdk.jol/jol-core/0.4/src/test/java/org_openjdk_jol/jol_core/HS_SA_CompressedReferencesProcessorTest.java) by stopping propagation of parent input args to helper JVMs and by capturing helper output concurrently.\n\nI rechecked `native-image --version` with `GRAALVM_HOME` and `JAVA_HOME` set to `/home/vjovanov/gdrive/bin/graalvm-jdk-25.0.3+9.1`, and then verified with the required command:\n```bash\nenv GRAALVM_HOME=/home/vjovanov/gdrive/bin/graalvm-jdk-25.0.3+9.1 \\\n    JAVA_HOME=/home/vjovanov/gdrive/bin/graalvm-jdk-25.0.3+9.1 \\\n    PATH=/home/vjovanov/gdrive/bin/graalvm-jdk-25.0.3+9.1/bin:$PATH \\\n    ./gradlew test -Pcoordinates=org.openjdk.jol:jol-core:0.4\n```\nThat run finished `BUILD SUCCESSFUL`."}}
